<TEXT>
marxist rebels of the western sahara said 
sunday they shot down a us locustspraying plane in the belief it 
was a moroccan military aircraft and they expressed their regrets 
all five american crewmen aboard the plane were killed on 
thursday when a groundtoair missile hit the dc7 and it crashed 
into the western sahara a disputed territory south of morocco a 
second dc7 chartered by the us agency for international 
development also was hit but it managed to land safely about 400 
miles away 
rebel fighters of the polisario front who are fighting morocco 
for independence of the western sahara thought the dc7s were 
moroccan c130 military planes polisario said in a telex from 
algiers to the associated press in new york 
the destruction of one of the two crafts was in no way 
premeditated it was an error caused by a pure coincidence stemming 
from the war conditions existing in the area and the moment that the 
planes arrived the statement said 
polisario said it found the wreckage of the plane and was 
beginning to retrieve the bodies of the victims it said the bodies 
would be returned to their families 
the rebel groups headquarters in algiers earlier denied that its 
units were involved in the attack 
sundays statement called the incident tragic and expressed 
polisarios deepest regrets to the world and deepest sorrow 
to the united states it said the rebels were convinced the incident 
would not hurt their friendly and trusting relations with the 
united states 
in washington state department spokesman rudy boone said there 
would be no immediate comment he said us officials would study 
the statement 
the rebel group said the unit that shot the missiles was carrying 
no equipment that would have enabled it to identify the planes 
it said the plane was attacked about 15 miles from a wall that 
morocco built in the western sahara to keep rebels from penetrating 
farther north into morocco 
it should be noted that the reconnaissance patrols along the 
wall come under daily attack from moroccan aircraft the statement 
said 
it said the planes were flying at the extremely low altitude of 
6000 feet the us embassy in rabat said shortly after the 
accident that the planes were attacked at about 10000 feet 
in rabat morocco a us embassy spokesman said saturday that 
the moroccan government pledged military protection to help a us 
team cross the rebelheld land to find the wreckage in the remote 
region of the sahara desert 
the planes which took off from senegal and were bound for 
morocco were on locustspraying missions none of the five 
crewmembers in the second plane was injured 
the pilot of the second plane joseph francis le gros told a 
news conference in agadir morocco that he saw a missile hit the 
first plane in an engine which caught fire the wing then fell off 
and the plane exploded before touching the ground he said 
officials have said the plane crashed about 35 miles southeast of 
the town of smara in the western sahara the spot lies halfway 
between the mauritanian border and the moroccan defense wall 
the rebels said in their statement sunday that the patrol that 
shot down the plane was also in the smara region of the western 
sahara at the time the moroccan government has maintained the 
planes were shot at from neighboring mauritania 
the us plane was the fifth aircraft shot down over the disputed 
territory since the sahara war broke out in 1975 previous incidents 
involved small french private aircraft 
the polisario movement seeks independence of the former spanish 
sahara territory annexed by morocco in 1976 after spain withdrew 
the united nations is holding talks in an effort to organize an 
independence referendum of the estimated 100000 inhabitants but 
the polisario says morocco should first withdraw 
the fbi in washington launched a criminal investigation friday 
into the missile attack it is looking for possible violations of 
us law such as one that deals with destruction of us aircraft 
overseas 
</TEXT>
