the fourth man indicted in a cross burning in 
front of a black familys home has pleaded guilty to federal charges 
in the case 
clifford j gilmer 23 of rural st clair county could be 
sentenced to up to 11 years in prison and fined as much as 350000 
for his role in the incident but prosecutors have agreed to seek 
less than the maximum sentence for all the men 
gilmer pleaded guilty friday to a count of conspiracy against the 
rights of citizens and a count of interfering with the civil rights 
of citizens through intimidation 
us district judge william beatty said gilmer would be sentenced 
feb 24 along with the other men who pleaded guilty earlier in the 
week prosecutors said the four defendants who are all white were 
not part of an organized racist group 
many people even as a prank might think of doing something 
like this but its a very serious federal offense said gilmers 
attorney robert rice i dont think any of them thought this was 
that serious but thats not a defense 
in return for gilmers guilty plea federal prosecutors dismissed 
a charge of using fire in a conspiracy against the rights of 
citizens 
willie and elsie carter who moved into a house around the corner 
from one of the defendants in june found the remains of the 
makeshift cross and its sawhorse base in their yard in the early 
morning of july 3 as they were preparing to leave for church 
the others charged in the case entered their pleas before beatty 
the previous week they are robert l mueller 31 mark mcintyre 
25 and marcus r schwartz 20 all of belleville 
mcintyre pleaded guilty to the conspiracy charge the others 
pleaded guilty to the same charges as gilmer 
