more than 200 people loudly but peacefully 
protested a small gathering saturday of white supremacist 
skinheads marking the death of a neonazi leader 
sheriffs deputies and state troopers tried to make sure the two 
groups stayed apart as the demonstrators carrying signs and 
chanting slogans circled in a parking lot at south whidbey state 
park on whidbey island about 35 miles northwest of seattle 
the skinheads who favor favor closecropped hair dark clothes 
and tattoos were not as visible 
terry doran regional manager for the washington state parks and 
recreation commission said about a dozen supremacists were at a 
group campsite inside the reserve and several others were elsewhere 
in the park 
doran said he was told the group planned a candlelight vigil for 
saturday night to commemorate the dec 9 1984 death of robert 
mathews founder of the violent neonazi group the order 
mathews died at age 31 in a shootout with fbi agents at a cabin 
on this mostly rural island after his death 22 order members were 
convicted or pleaded guilty after being indicted on racketeering 
charges they were accused of robberies that netted more than 4 
million and other crimes including the june 1984 murder of alan 
berg a jewish talkradio host in denver 
john metzger leader of the white aryan resistance youth had 
called for a vigil on whidbey island to mark mathews death metzger 
is the son of tom metzger founder of the fallbrook califbased 
white aryan resistance the group most active in the recent spread 
of neonazism among the youthful followers of the skinhead 
subculture 
police guarded the campsite turning away anyone not part of the 
group including reporters and photographers 
charlie james a community activist from seattle said an 
organization called united front against facism chartered three 
buses to bring antinazi demonstrators to the park 
im here to protest against the bigotry the hatred and the 
killing said kay prater of seattle one of the demonstrators she 
carried a sign reading you are next speak out against bigotry 
