<TEXT>
if christmas always seems to bring out 
that feeling of oh what fun it isnt to pick out the tree take 
heart things are looking up 
cultivating christmas trees once a disorganized endeavor is 
fast becoming a sophisticated industry and there are more and better 
trees to choose from 
the business of christmas trees has become a mature type of 
enterprise said david baumann associate director of the 
33yearold national christmas tree association in milwaukee 
people are getting very knowledgeable on what they need to grow 
market and care for trees 
anyone who has gone to the local lot and agonized over what 
always seems like the most important decision of the holiday season 
knows that hasnt always been the case 
in the 1950s nearly 90 percent of the trees sold in the united 
states came from natural stands where people went in the woods and 
cut them down what you saw was what you got consequently most 
markets suffered shortages and most of what did arrive on the lot 
was of inferior quality 
twenty years ago they were cutting a lot of trees out of the 
wild said hal schudel who operates holiday tree farms in 
corvallis ore with his three sons and oftentimes they were cut 
way back in early october those trees then laid around and they 
might be pretty good but theyd dry out 
the big breakthrough for farmers was the realization that to 
control quality and improve harvesting techniques they had to 
operate on a plantation basis the ncta estimates that 90 percent of 
the trees sold now are grown on plantations 
we gradually saw the light says schudel who has been in the 
business for over 30 years and sells between 400000 and 500000 
trees a year from his farm on the fringe of the cascade mountains 
we decided to plant trees in rows to see if we could grow them 
that way as a farmer would his corn we were able to control weeds 
better and spray our crop to protect it from the weeds and brush 
and we were able to grow more trees per acre and manage it as a 
crop 
shortages which aided the dramatic rise in popularity of the 
artificial tree no longer are a problem not even the severe 
drought that hampered farmers throughout the summer has put a dent 
in this years harvest the ncta expects a record 341 million trees 
will be cut for the holidays an increase of 800000 over last year 
the growers in this country have come a long way in producing a 
good quality product said schudel who brings much of his harvest 
down from the mountains by helicopter to ensure its freshness 
theres plenty of trees of good quality available now if 
distribution is good theres no need to settle for anything but a 
good tree 
today farmers have set their sights on growing the ultimate tree 
the whole effort is toward the perfect tree baumann said 
people dont want a charlie brown christmas tree 
for the most part the consumer isnt getting that anymore using 
the latest horticultural technology trees are nurtured fertilized 
and pruned for the eight to 15 years it takes them to grow from 
eight to 10inch seedlings into full symmetrical trees six to 
seven feet tall 
some still do it the oldfashioned way 
we used to pick our own seeds from about 40 bushels of cones 
said florence belle whos worked in the business for more than 40 
years and has a stand of 1000 saplings on her property near saranac 
lake in the adirondack mountains then wed put them on racks and 
dry them out 
growers in michigan which along with oregon produces upward of 6 
million trees the most in the nation have begun tagging many of 
their trees in an effort to demonstrate that their product is a 
notch above the competition and farmers in illinois indiana 
oregon washington california and new york are following suit 
growers want trees grown in their state to be known in the same 
way that idaho potatoes or florida oranges are known baumann said 
according to figures compiled by the ncta demand for real trees 
has grown an average of 22 percent a year over the past decade in 
a recent study conducted by pennsylvania state university 39 
percent of the households surveyed used real trees and 35 percent 
had artificial ones while 26 percent did not have a tree 
the ncta is helping out with a milliondollar television ad 
campaign its first ever the spots which started airing right 
after thanksgiving feature weatherman willard scott urging watchers 
to have a real tree merry christmas 
growers maintain a real tree is still a bargain too 
we can measure retail prices baumann said and what weve 
discovered is that over the last 20 years theyve gone up about half 
the rate of the consumer price index 
the association said 1988 retail prices should range from 300 
to 525 a foot varying with the quality of the tree and local 
market conditions 
