blows peoples minds said robert wilson an assistant professor 
of environmental health sciences at the university of rochester 
but he said that number is nearly as frightening as it sounds 
because studies on the dangers of methylene chloride are very 
equivocal 
methylene chloride a powerful solvent thats used in paint 
strippers spray paint and as an industrial solvent is at the 
center of this environmental controversy 
kodak the largest user of the solvent in new york uses it 
around the clock as a key ingredient in the manufacture of miles and 
miles of photographic film 
within the last 10 years the safety of exposure to the chemical 
has come under scrutiny and in 1985 the chemical was listed as a b2 
probable carcinogen by the environmental protection agency 
that means that theres sufficient evidence from research in 
animals to indicate that a chemical could cause cancer but no 
evidence in humans 
in fact the epa used a comprehensive kodak study of its own 
workers exposed to the chemical to determine that there were no 
significant increases in the incidence of cancer 
in october the company gathered a panel of 16 experts to review 
the current information on methylene chloride and offer an opinion 
on the danger of exposure to the chemical 
the bottom line is that when the panel members were asked if 
they would be content to live in an atmosphere that contained what 
rochesters contained the answer was absolutely said dr 
marvin kuschner chairman of the panel and a professor of pathology 
at the state university of new york at stony brook 
the final piece of the pollution puzzle occurred last month when 
with concerns of pollution at their height kodak requested a permit 
to release additional methylene chloride into the air because of its 
planned expansion 
the company is challenging the states recently revised limits on 
emissions and the state has promised a ruling later this month 
i dont know why all these things have happened at the same 
time i dont have the luxury to think about that said al butkas 
chief supervisor of kodak affairs for the state department of 
environmental conservation it would have been a lot nicer if each 
one of these things had come in separate fiveyear blocks i can 
tell you that 
